        <svcproc svcproctype="replace" graphiccount="22">
            <title>Service Procedure</title>
            <specpara>
                <important>
                    <para>
                        <emph type="bold">Upon completion of the repair call the ArvinMeritor Ontrac call center, (866)
                            668-7221, to register the repair and to obtain a repair authorization number and retrofit
                            number. These numbers will need to be included on your claim to International Truck and
                            Engine.
                        </emph>
                    </para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>To avoid possible property damage, personal injury, or death, park the vehicle on a level
                        surface, set the parking brake, turn the engine off and chock the wheels.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>This transfer case service procedure is performed without removing the transfer case from the
                        chassis.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Drain the oil from the transfer case.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install an air line fitting into the high range port (Figure 1 and Figure 2) and apply
                    100 PSI max. regulated shop air. Rotate the input shaft to lock the range gear.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Maintain air pressure during removal of the input shaft and during reinstallation Steps. This
                        will aid alignment of the high range gear and rear input shaft bearing.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0490301" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490301.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 1. Install Air Line Fitting</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0490302" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490302.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 2. Attach Regulated Shop Air (100 PSI Max.)</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. High Range Port</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. Neutral Port</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. Low Range Port</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">4208 (Code 13TKC) / 4210 (Code 13TKA) Models Only:</emph>
                    Remove bolts and cover from the transfer case rear cover (Figure 3).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0490303" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490303.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="248px"/>
                <caption>Figure 3. Remove Rear Cover (4208/4210 Models Only)</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove hex lock nut with special hex socket tool
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0490322">(Figure 22)</hotlnk>
                    and washer from the range gear shaft (Figure 4).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0490304" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490304.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 4. Remove Hex Lock Nut and Washer</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the propshaft from between the transfer case and the main transmission.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect the oil inlet tube fitting and move the oil tube out of position for
                    clearance (Figure 5).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0490305" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490305.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 5. Disconnect and Reposition Oil Tube</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Loosen input yoke nut (do not remove).</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove bolts from the bearing cage on the front cover (Figure 6).</para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0490306" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490306.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 6. Remove Bolts from Bearing Cage</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Use a dead blow hammer to aid removal in Step 9.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the input shaft with yoke, input bearing cage, and oil pump as an assembly
                    (Figure 7).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0490307" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490307.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="248px"/>
                <caption>Figure 7. Remove Input Shaft and Yoke Assembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove shims and put aside for re-assembly.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Place the input shaft assembly in a vise with jaw protection and remove the yoke with a
                    puller (Figure 8).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove input shaft bearing cage and oil pump assembly from the input shaft (Figure 8).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0490308" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490308.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 8. Remove Bearing Cage and Oil Pump Assembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect helical gear and shaft for damage. Replace if required.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the spiral snap ring that retains the small helical gear on the input shaft
                    (Figure 9) and replace it with the snap ring supplied in the kit. Ensure that the snap ring is fully
                    seated in the snap ring groove.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0490309" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490309.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 9. Remove Snap Ring</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install new input shaft seal, using Meritor oil seal driver Part Number R4422402, on the
                    new input cage (Figure 10). Prelube with SAE 50 synthetic oil.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Cage part number A3226Z1482 must be used with pump part number A3303G1047.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0490310" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490310.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 10. Install New Input Shaft Seal</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Male Fitting (Inlet Oil Port)</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. Seal Driver</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove male fitting from the old cage (Figure 10, Item 1), chase the threads if needed,
                    apply appropriate pipe thread sealant to the first three threads and install in the new input cage.
                    Tighten to 35 to 50 Lbf-ft (47 to 68 Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install new o-ring onto the groove along the input cage outside diameter. Prelube with
                    SAE 50 synthetic oil (Figure 11).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0490311" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490311.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="272px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 11. Install New O-ring</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install new bearing cone on the race in the bearing cage. Prelube with SAE 50 synthetic
                    oil.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the relief valve and spring into correct (square) port location in the bearing
                    cage (Figure 12).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>The large end of the spring goes in first.</para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <figure id="f0490312" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490312.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 12. Install Relief Valve Spring</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Align oil relief port and inlet port. Pour a generous amount of oil into the pump oil
                    inlet port (Figure 13) while spinning the inner rotor by hand before assembling the oil pump to the
                    input cage. Loosely install two, pump to cage, bolts to aid alignment during installation on the
                    shaft (Figure 14).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0490313" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490313.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="408px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 13. Align New Oil Pump</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Oil Relief and Inlet Ports</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0490314" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490314.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 14. Loosely Install Two Bolts</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Inspect the seal rings on the pump inner diameter and pre-lube with SAE 50 synthetic
                    oil.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>When performing the next Step, make sure the input cage and oil pump are aligned. Use bolts in
                        the bolt holes to aid alignment.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Pre-lube the input shaft with SAE 50 synthetic oil.
                    <emph type="bold">Use extreme care when guiding the oil pump assembly onto the input shaft.</emph>
                    Be sure to align the spline with the pump rotor. Do not force pump/cage assembly if it hangs up.
                    After bottoming the pump/cage assembly onto the shaft shoulder, apply Loctite 277 to the pump bolts
                    and tighten to 22 to 29 Lbf-ft (29 to 39 Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Pre-lube the yoke hub seal diameter with SAE 50 synthetic oil.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the yoke, washer, and nut onto the input shaft. Do not tighten at this time.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Before installing the input shaft assembly into the transfer case, inspect and clean the
                    transfer case input shaft, cage to housing pilot surfaces and cage mounting surface. Remove any
                    debris and Loctite sealant from mounting surfaces.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Position the old shim pack over the front input shaft opening with guide studs. The
                    opening between the shim pack ends (split) should face downward.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Lubricate the rear input bearing race and range gear with SAE 50 synthetic lube.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the speed sensor and install a screwdriver or equivalent into the speed sensor
                    bore to hold and guide the range gear in position.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the input shaft assembly (Figure 15). Use an assistant to rotate the output yoke
                    while holding pressure against the mating range gear with the screw driver to aid installation of
                    the input shaft assembly (Figure 16).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0490315" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490315.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="352px"/>
                <caption>Figure 15. Install Input Shaft Assembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0490316" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490316.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="312px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 16. Rotate Output Shaft Yoke and Apply Pressure with Screwdriver</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>It may require several attempts to line up the input shaft assembly to the housing. It is
                        possible for the shaft to hang up on the rear input bearing or high range gear.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <warning>
                    <para>A jack must never be used alone to support a vehicle while under-chassis service is being
                        performed. The jack may lower and property damage, personal injury or death could result. Always
                        support the vehicle with floor stands.
                    </para>
                </warning>
            </specpara>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>If necessary, raise the drive wheels off the floor, release the brakes and rotate the drive
                        wheels to help align the input shaft to the housing.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">When the input shaft assembly is seated in the transfer case, install three (3) bolts,
                    equally spaced, to attach the input shaft cage to the transfer case (Figure 17). Tighten to 85 to
                    115 lbf-ft (115 to 156 Nm).
                    <emph type="bold">Do not use an impact wrench.</emph>
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0490317" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490317.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="352px"
                         scalefitheight="352px"/>
                <caption>Figure 17. Install Input Shaft Assembly</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">At the rear of the transfer case install the washer and nut to the shaft. Tightened to
                    700 to 900 Lbf-ft (949 to 1220 Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Check shaft end play (.001 to .005 inch) with a dial indicator.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Adjust the shim pack as required with shims provided. The final endplay must be .001 to
                    .005 inch.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">A.</emph>Install remaining mounting bolts into the input shaft bearing cage
                    (Figure 17). Tighten to 85 to 115 Lbf-ft (115 to 156 Nm).
                </para>
                <para>
                    <emph type="bold">B.</emph>Tighten the yoke to 700 to 900 Lbf-ft (949 to 1220 Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">4208 (Code 13TKC) / 4210 (Code 13TKA) Models Only:</emph>
                    Clean rear cover mounting surface and cover flange.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">
                    <emph type="bold">4208 (Code 13TKC) / 4210 (Code 13TKA) Models Only:</emph>
                    Apply Loctite 518 sealant to the rear cover mounting surface and install the rear cover. Tighten the
                    bolts to 45 to 60 Lbf-ft (61 to 81 Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Reconnect the oil inlet tube. Tighten to 79 to 88 Lbf-ft (107 to 119 Nm).</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect the air line (Figure 2) and remove the air fitting from the high range port.
                    Reconnect the high range line to the high range port.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Reinstall the speed sensor. Tighten the cap screws retaining the sensor to 96 to 120
                    Lbf-in (11 to 14 Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Disconnect the air lines from the high/low range shift cylinder and remove the shift
                    cylinder from the rear cover of the transfer case (Figure 18).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0490318" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490318.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 18. Remove Shift Cylinder (Arrow)</caption>
            </figure>
            <figure id="f0490319" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490319.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="288px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 19. Disconnect Air Lines</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Low Range Port</callout1>
                    <callout1>2. Neutral Port</callout1>
                    <callout1>3. High Range Port</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the outer shift piston snap ring from the shift shaft and remove the shift piston
                    (Figure 20).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0490320" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490320.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 20. Remove Outer Piston</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Outer Piston</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the inner shift piston snap ring from the shift shaft and remove the shift piston
                    (Figure 21).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0490321" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490321.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="312px"/>
                <caption>Figure 21. Remove Inner Piston</caption>
                <calloutgroup>
                    <callout1>1. Inner Piston</callout1>
                </calloutgroup>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the inner and outer piston O-rings.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Grease all new replacement O-rings with a light coat of lithium grease meeting Meritor
                    specification O-688.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install O-rings onto the inner and outer diameter of the inner piston. Install the inner
                    shift piston and snap ring onto the shift shaft (refer to Figure 21). Inner piston can be installed
                    in either direction.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install O-rings onto the inner and outer diameter of the outer piston. Install the inner
                    shift piston and snap ring onto the shift shaft (refer to Figure 20).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Apply a 1/8 inch (3 mm) bead of Loctite&#174; 277 sealant to the first three threads of
                    the shift cylinder.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the high/low shift cylinder. Tighten the cylinder to 85 to 95 Lbf-ft (115 to 129
                    Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Reinstall the air lines on the high/ low shift cylinder.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Fill the transfer case with 9.0 pints (4.26 Liters) of SAE 50 synthetic lubricant.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Reinstall the prop shaft between the transfer case and the main transmission.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Perform
                    <emph type="bold">Shifting Check</emph>
                    and
                    <emph type="bold">Assembly Test</emph>. Refer to Meritor Maintenance Manual 0146 for details. These
                    tests insure there are no housing or shift port leaks.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Meritor MTC-4208 (Code 13TKC), 4210 (13TKA) or 4213 (13TKB) transfer case is limited to 3250
                        RPM maximum. It is important to verify the vehicle configuration will not over speed the
                        transfer case.
                    </para>
                    <para>To establish maximum vehicle road speed allowed for a given vehicle, perform the following
                        calculation:
                    </para>
                    <para>195000 &#247; REAR AXLE RATIO &#247; REAR TIRE REVOLUTIONS PER MILE = MAXIMUM ROAD SPEED
                    </para>
                    <para>Example: 195000 &#247; 5.57 &#247;497 =70.4 MPH</para>
                    <para>In this example, 70.4 MPH is the maximum road speed that this vehicle can operate without
                        exceeding the 3250 RPM transfer case limit. To exceed this limit may cause transfer case oil
                        pump damage.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <para>
                <title>Special Tool</title>
            </para>
            <para>Meritor Part Number 3256Z1144 can be fabricated as shown in Figure 22.</para>
            <figure id="f0490322" figsize="pg-wide">
                <graphic filename="../afcfigures/g0490322.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="514px"/>
                <caption>Figure 22. Special Hex Socket Tool</caption>
            </figure>
